  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Inscription on the Newly Cast Bell of Yeonbok Temple
  author: Lee Gok
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the spring of the sixth year of Zhizheng, the Esteemed Minister Jiang of the Bureau of Imperial Counselors and Vice Director Xin of the Left Treasury arrived bearing the Son of Heaven's mandate and golden gifts, to cast a great bell upon Mount Geumgang. In that season, the villages around the mountain suffered famine, and the people eagerly gathered at the foundry, earning their sustenance through honest labor. When the bell was completed, the Minister prepared to return to court. The King and Princess then addressed their ministers, saying: "Mount Geumgang lies within our realm. Now the Sage Son of Heaven has sent his trusted servants to magnify the Buddhist teachings and perpetuate their glory. What contribution can we, lacking even a thread's worth of aid, make to repay such grace?" The ministers replied: "The great bell of Yeonbok Temple has long fallen into disuse. Now that skilled craftsmen have come to our land, let us recast it anew. This too shall honor the imperial will and create an imperishable merit." They brought this proposal to the Minister, who gladly consented and postponed his departure to see it accomplished. The King commanded me, Gok, to inscribe this bell.

    Hear the golden voice unite all ears—
    It marshals three armies, harmonizes eight tones.
    The Buddha's teaching runs deeper than the sea;
    What darkness dwells beneath the earth's deep layers!
    Millions die and are reborn in endless suffering,
    Dreaming and drunken, deaf and mute to truth.
    One sound of the bell—the heart awakens!

    Yeonbok Temple stands in the royal capital,
    A vast sanctuary of the dharma.
    The new bell tolls once—
    All the southern realm trembles.
    Upward it pierces the boundless sky,
    Downward it reaches the darkest hells.
    All beings receive the gift of purity and splendor.

    Our kingdom's sovereign and ministers three times make wish:
    May the Son of Heaven reign ten thousand years,
    May he father sons without end,
    May his blessings extend to the farthest lands.
    I am commanded to carve these words upon the bell,
    That they endure for ages untold.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Mount Geumgang (金剛山): The sacred mountain revered in both Buddhism and Korean tradition, located in Korean territory but also venerated throughout East Asia.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'The eight tones (八音): A traditional classification of musical instruments in Chinese music theory, symbolizing universal harmony.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Yeonbok Temple (演福寺): A major Buddhist temple where this bell was to be installed as a focal point of practice and worship.'
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to 'three armies' and 'eight tones' draws on Confucian principles of order and harmony while maintaining Buddhist spiritual significance.
